    {
      "id": "3b1b820e705675b803fe0e8f69c05dee40e9c9d6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-03-15 07:11:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, approved\n\n(2 inline comments)\n\nPatch looks fine, and quite a lot of old code deleted.\n\nInline comments are just advisory, nothing wrong with the patch itself.  I would have deleted the old 2.6.17 kernel code in the same patch, since this code was already being modified and to avoid patch dependencies.  However, since this patch is already here and looks fine, we may as well stick with it as-is and hopefully there is another patch in the series that deletes this old code.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "cbfaa217fc1c796e8e536ff6e1e96da69d2c8296",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 179,
        "name": "Peng Tao",
        "email": "bergwolf@gmail.com",
        "username": "bergwolf"
      },
      "date": "2012-03-15 07:40:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi Andreas,\n\nI do realize that KERNEL_VERSION() should be removed but I also noticed that darwin has\n#define LINUX_VERSION_CODE KERNEL_VERSION(2,5,0)\nSo these KERNEL_VERSION macros seem to be effective to MacOS port.\n\nI saw the email your sent out about removing NT/MacOS support. Should I leave KERNEL_VERSION as is until the decision about MacOS is made? If you think that it can be removed now, I can send a new patch to do it separately.\n\nThanks a lot for reviewing!",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "6958abfcbae7563ac0846c293fa398888b96a6f1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-03-15 09:15:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI think the use of LINUX_VERSION_CODE for non-Linux architectures is ancient.  I see only a handful of uses in the existing tree, and they are all in Linux-specific code (llite, lvfs) so could not possibly be in use by the MacOS port (which has its own VFS layer due to the many differences from the Linux VFS layer, and only runs on the client).\n\nIt should be fine to remove any mention of LINUX_VERSION_CODE from the darwin and liblustre directories.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c72a5e89487b5b063dacae3d0ba01ab217ea8e26",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2012-03-15 21:43:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.2/x86_64, CentOS release 5.7/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/3b76553a-6ee5-11e1-b737-5254004bbbd3).  Ran 13 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0045e56e75cfaf7089cf7966aaf514ee0b86ab6e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2012-03-20 04:36:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, approved\n\nThis looks good.\n\nIt should be noted that in fact intent file and cache_head.ref are two completely unrelated pieces of code and would have made two great separate patches.\n(not that I request you to split them now, just for the future).\n\nThanks",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b279a7359c791643e5953698f30d58227bac4595",
      "author": {
